Instead I suggest to only log the output of the {{JohnsonFilter}} once and not on every request.

Ideally, the default (OnDemand) configuration should not do any access logging and if so do it into a separate log file which can have a different log rotation rule applied.

{quote}
One last issue I would like to point out is notifications to users when they commit a file into a repo.
They forever get notifications from that plan. Even if they’ve moved on to another project/team.
Having a feature to disable notifications when the user is no longer in the plan would also be great.
{quote}

Supposing that a user gets created in an LDAP system with an incorrect name, gets synced in Bamboo, and only then gets corrected in LDAP, that user's incorrect name is stuck in Bamboo and cannot be corrected through the administration panel.

The current workaround for that is to run this SQL query directly at database level:
{code:sql}
update external_entities set name = '<new user name>' where name = '<old user name>';
{code}

But that is a really gnarly workaround.

Deployment failed to get variables substituted in second run of failed deployment.

The variables are set in plan configuration e.g.
# ${bamboo.version_major}
# ${bamboo.version_minor}
# ${bamboo.version_patch}

These variables are used in *Release Versioning* and called in *Command* task in an environment as _$\{bamboo.deploy.version\}_.

A re-run of a failed deployment will failed with following error:
{noformat}
ERROR: ${bamboo.version_major\}.${bamboo.version_minor\}.${bamboo.version_patch\} is not a valid version!
{noformat}

{quote}

"Create" shortcut in Jira works just perfect: every user want to create new tickets every time. But this button in Bamboo is completely irrelevant. I seldom create new plan or deployment project. I think instead of this I should be able to quickly run new build or deploy particular project. Bamboo can save 3-5 last builds and deploys I ran recently and give me shortcut to run them again. For example, I want to run new build: I press "Run" shortcut and choose "Build BuildPlanA from ProjectB", and then new build for this plan will be started and I will be redirected to this build plan page. Or I can press "Run" shortcut and choose "DeployProjectA to EnvironmentB". This will be awesome user experience I think.

{quote}

h5. Reproducing the issue
# open "{{<bamboo-home>/bamboo.cfg.xml}}" and add a expired license to:
{code}
<property name="license.string">ADD EXPIRED LICENSE</property>
{code}
# start Bamboo on a web browser. Please make sure you have clean your cache and cookies before run this test.

h5. Error thrown in the browser
{code}
Uncaught SyntaxError: Unexpected token < 
{code}
!bamboo561.expiredLicense.png|thumbnail!

*Workaround:*
1. Stop Bamboo completely
2. Open bamboo.cfg.xml file located under <bamboo-home> directory
3. Replace the "license.string" property with the new license and save the file:
{code}
<property name="license.string">ABCD</property>
{code}
4. Starting Bamboo now will show the login screen correctly

We have a script that downloads the artifacts of the last successful build from Bamboo.

Updating the script to work with S3 required to change the hard coded url from
{noformat}
${BAMBOO_BASE_URL}/artifact/${PLAN_KEY}/${JOB_KEY}/build-latestSuccessful/${ARTEFACT_NAME}/${ARTEFACT_PATH}
{noformat}

to
{noformat}
${BAMBOO_BASE_URL}/build/artifactUrlRedirect.action?planKey=${PLAN_KEY}-${JOB_KEY}&buildNumber=${build_number}&artifactName=${ARTEFACT_NAME}&tag=${ARTEFACT_PATH}
{noformat}

But using the new scheme requires to pass an existing build number (leaving it blank won't work as expected, too).

Having to search the latest build number upfront feels a little bit odd to me: first I ask for the latest build and then I pass this along in a second request. Instead, Bamboo should support something like symbolic build numbers which are resolved on Bamboo side.

Related to this is the problem of resolving the latest successful build number which normally requires extensive JSON / XML processing of the result returned by a REST resource. If Bamboo would support something like {{latestSuccessful}} for the redirect directly, that avoid requiring every user / customer to write its own script around the REST resources - that would be great.

Thanks!

The recently introduced feature of tighter integration between Bamboo and stash where when the 2 apps are linked through application link, the repositories from stash are consumable in Bamboo works in such a way that bamboo saves a key in the user profile for authentication. This feature was introduced in Bamboo 5.6. See https://confluence.atlassian.com/display/BAMBOO/Stash

{quote}
Stash must have SSH access enabled: When you link to a Stash repository, Bamboo generates an SSH key pair that it shares with Stash. See Enabling SSH access to Git repositories in Stash. If you want to view the public SSH key in Stash, see SSH access keys for system use.
{quote}

It will be nice to have this key shared and stored against the projects in Stash instead for the reason that the user in stash could be deactivated in future. For example if the user no longer works for the company. In situations like this, the build in Bamboo will fail and we need to login as a different user to update all the linked repositories to get this working
